## Exception

I can run/debug other things (`lib/main.dart`), but `Flutter test` configurations don't seem to work. By default (clicking run or debug in the context menu in the project window creates a `Dart test` run configuration instead of `Flutter test`, but manually creating a `Flutter test` config instead causes above error message.

I think this is since the update to the new Flutter plugin version.
At least I'm quite sure this still worked a few days ago and the test is only a very basic example test.

comment_data.body:
/cc @pq 

We should fail better here; @zoechi, from that assert message, it looks like there may not be a test file or directory set for the test launch configuration?
"Test scope" "All in file" and "Test file" are set.
Tracing through things I'm wondering if there isn't something curious about your project structure.  Do you have a pubspec?  A `.packages` file?  A `lib` directory?

Yes, all there. It already worked fine some days ago. I think the latest plugin update broke it.
I'm not sure though and couldn't find a way to downgrade.

Hmmm.  Out of curiosity, what happens if you delete the configuration and create a new one?  Or what if you create another test and try and run it?

Thanks for the help in tracking this down @zoechi!

I recreated the configuration several times without effect.
It doesn't seem related to the content. I commented out everything so it only contains an empty main, but no difference.
The test runs fine with `flutter test test/unit_test.dart`

I created a new test. 
When I launched it using the context menu, it created a Dart test run config, instead of a Flutter test config.
Creating a Flutter test config manually, I got again above error mrssage.

A plugin update today didn't change anything.

Thanks!

Could you check that the Dart SDK set in Preferences is the same for Dart as it is under Flutter?

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/67586/31401542-0be45788-ada8-11e7-9523-e5d11e03ef52.png)
Yes, they are pointing to the same directory (Dart 2 directories deeper)

Thanks for the follow-up.  One more thing to try...

Does this same problem arise with a fresh project?

That is, if you create a new Flutter project and try and run the sample test, are you seeing the same behavior?

I couldn't reproduce in a new project created with `flutter create`.
I want to investigate further, but I don't have too much time currently.

Thanks @zoechi.  No need to bang on this.  Let's re-open if it recurs or if we get a lead on a repro.

As always, your help is really appreciated!
